t public works projects in large part because of his reliability, his empathy with the developmentalist project of Mexican President Porfirio Díaz, and his assiduous cultivation of a clientelist network within the Mexican political elite. His success thus provides an opportunity to reappraise the role played by overseas interests in the national development of Mexico.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBusinessmenxBiographyxGreat Britain. 0aBusinessmenzGreat BritainvBiography. 0aCorporations, BritishxHistoryxMexico. 0aCorporations, BritishzMexicoxHistory. 0aEngineersxBiographyxGreat Britain. 0aEngineerszGreat BritainvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804779036zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804779036423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804779036.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles